solution.p:
From the formulas for  X_{\text{CM}}  and  Y_{\text{CM}} ,.

	 \amp X_{\text{CM}} =  \dfrac{2\times (-4) + 3\times 0 + 4 \times 0}{2+3+4} = -\dfrac{8}{9} 
	 \amp Y_{\text{CM}} =  \dfrac{2\times 0 + 3\times 0 + 4 \times 3}{2+3+4} = \dfrac{4}{3} 

Therefore, the CM is located at  (-\dfrac{8}{9}\text{ m}, \dfrac{4}{3}\text{ m}) in the coordinate system in the figure. Note that these values will changes if we use another coordinate system, but the physical location of the CM will remain the same.

subsection.p:
For the general case of  N  part system, we will have to start with equations of motion of individual parts in the momentum form.

	 \amp \vec F_1 = \dfrac{d\vec p_1}{dt} 
	 \amp \vec F_2 = \dfrac{d\vec p_2}{dt}  
	 \amp \cdots 
	 \amp \vec F_N = \dfrac{d\vec p_N}{dt}  

Now, summing them, we get the left side to equal the  F_{\text{net}}^{\text{ext}}  as above, and the right side equals the rate of change of total momentum.

	F_{\text{net}}^{\text{ext}} = \dfrac{d}{dt} \left( \vec p_1 + \vec p_2 + \cdots + \vec p_N \right).

But by Eq. , we can replace the sum of momenta of the parts by the center-of-mass momentum.

	F_{\text{net}}^{\text{ext}} = \dfrac{d \vec P_{\text{CM}}}{dt},

where  \vec P_{\text{CM}} = M \vec V_{\text{CM}}. This equation takes care of even those situations in which the total mass of the system is changing, regardless of which part it that may be losing mass. Of course, if a system is not losing mass, we would use much simpler analysis based on Eq. .
